However, EVERY student said the best part of their day was seeing their friends and their teachers. As their teacher,it was a gentle reminder that we are still making an impact, even from afar." #D33Pride #D33Orgullo #TogetherforExcellence
~Morgan Parise, 1ST Grade, Indian Knoll

shared_text:
WeGo Together for Kids
September 3 at 9:22 PM ¬∑

Thank you to everyone that attended our backpack bash today. Over 500 students received a backpack filled with supplies. We understand the frustration with the early start time. At 2:30PM we already had 50 cars in line and since it was a first come first serve event, we felt it was appropriate to start early.

We also want to thank the many donors including staff from Northwestern Medicine, Wise Plastics, and the South-Southwest Regional Board of Directors for United Way of Metro Chicago and the volunteers and West Chicago Elementary School District 33 staff that allowed us to support so many students as they begin the new school year.

Our Family Ties: A Breath of Fresh Parenting Education Podcast's newest episode is about helping our family cope with change and loss-

shared_text:
DAILYHERALD.COM
West Chicago church to host new COVID-19 testing site

St. Andrew Lutheran Church, located in West Chicago IL
June 17 at 11:57 PM ¬∑

West Chicago is one of the hardest-hit communities because residents who do not have the privilege of working from home during the pandemic face higher risk, said the Rev. Josh Ebener, pastor of St. Andrew Lutheran Church, a multicultural parish.

"A lot of our folks in our community have the essential jobs," Ebener said Wednesday. "They're working in factories where we're seeing a lot of these cases. In our own parish, we've had several cases."

St. Andrew runs an emergency food assistance program that reaches about 250 people each Saturday. The church will now host the testing center operated by VNA Health Care, a nonprofit provider, starting June 23.

"It's an economic and health crisis, and the two are inseparable," Ebener said. "We certainly think that we need to work on both of those fronts, and I think welcoming a testing center in our community here is a real big part of that."

post_text:
Special Education for Home Schooled Children

On Monday, June 1, 2020 from 8:30-9:00 am, a Timely Meaningful Consultation meeting conducted by the West Chicago Elementary School District 33 will be held virtually. Since the meeting will be held virtually, you will need to provide an email or you will receive a phone number and pin code to join the meeting, please call 630-293-6000 (option 3) to participate. The purpose of the meeting will be to discuss the district‚Äôs plans for providing special education services to students with disabilities who attend private schools in our community or are residents electing to home school their child for the 2020-21 school year. If you are the parent of a homeschooled student who has been identified or may be identified with a disability and you reside within the boundaries of West Chicago Elementary School District 33, you are urged to attend. If you have any further questions or need additional information, please contact us.

post_text:
Please help us welcome the newest member to the District 33 Board of Education, Felicia Gills.

Her love for children and education is what prompted her to apply for the position on the Board. She is happy to see the growth and advancement the district has made over the last decade. However, more excited to see where the City of West Chicago, local business leaders, and the community can take this next generation of youth we are responsible for today. Felicia looks forward to serving the rich diverse culture of all 4,458 students here in D33.

Read more about Felicia here: http://www.wego33.org/

May 25 at 9:00 AM ¬∑

On the last Monday of May, our fine country celebrates Memorial Day. Although this year's holiday looks a little different than it has in the past, with social distancing and masks. Let's remember the meaning behind today...a day for us to remember and honor those who have served in the U.S. military, who fought for our freedom and who lost their lives while doing so. To them we say thank you!

Have a safe holiday West Chicago!

The arts are alive and truly amazing in District 33!

On Fridays, we will feature projects and performances by our students in celebration of Illinois being the first state to include the arts -dance, media arts, music, theatre, and visual arts - along with subjects like math, reading and science, in how the state measures the impact of every public school in Illinois. #thed33effect #ILSchoolsStepUp #D33Pride #D33Orgullo Arts Alliance Illinois

D33 band and orchestra programs are taught by talented and passionate teachers who continue to instruct students virtually.

shared_text:
People Made Visible
May 20 at 10:02 AM ¬∑

West Chicago now has the highest number of positive COVID-19 cases in DuPage County and we must all take precautions to stop the spread and keep everyone healthy and safe! As we go into Memorial Day weekend, please abide by the Phase 2 guidelines which prohibits any nonessential gathering. For more information and phone hotline support, visit the DuPage County Health Department website https://www.dupagehealth.org/590/Coronavirus-Disease-2019-COVID-19-Inform.

Need resources in Spanish: https://www.advocateaurorahealth.org/coronavirus-disease-2019/espanol.

There are also many struggling with mental health issues as we face unprecedented times. There are free resources to help: https://www.dupagehealth.org/618/Maintaining-Your-Mental-Health You can also text TALK to 552020 for English or HABLAR for Spanish and receive free and anonymous support.

As a community we can work together to get through this! Stay informed to protect each other and yourselves.

post_text:
ATTENTION D33 FAMILIES:

Food Distribution and Tech Device Support Canceled Until Further Notice!

Earlier today, we were notified that an Aramark food service employee tested positive for COVID-19. This person is currently receiving care, and I know I speak for everyone when I say that our thoughts are with this person and their family.
This individual is currently in a role with Aramark that does not typically come in direct contact with students or families. At this point it appears that this person likely only had contact with a few individuals, and those individuals will be asked to stay home for two weeks, monitor themselves for symptoms and stay in regular contact with their health care providers.

Out of an abundance of caution, and to ensure the safety of our students, their families and staff, food distribution, work packets and tech device support will be suspended until further notice and the district offices will be closed until Monday, May 18, 2020.
https://bit.ly/3bWj0sU

A special message from Mrs. Lay, 7th grade assistant principal!

Exploratory selection is coming in May! LOTS more details will follow.

To prepare, we are asking students to check that they can log into the Home Access Center. Students will need to use their STUDENT log-in for Home Access Center to select their Exploratory classes. Have you ever considered what it would be like to be a District 33 school board member?

Do you have a willingness to collaborate and a sincere interest in the education of the children in District 33?

Then NOW is your chance! The board is now accepting online applications to fill a 12-month unexpired term.

Requirements for board members include the following:
Must be a United States citizen,
Must be at least 18 years of age,
Must be a District 33 community member for at least one year,
Must be a registered voter
Must not hold another incompatible public office position.

This is not a paid position.

Online Application is found on our website. http://www.wego33.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=6G0GU0B&dasi=4GBP0

shared_text:
WeGo Together for Kids
April 17 at 4:51 PM ¬∑

Today, in partnership with volunteers from Wheaton Bible Church, 83 families received home deliveries of care packages filled with essential supplies like diapers, toilet paper, feminine hygiene products, hand sanitizer, and first-aid kits. We will be working alongside West Chicago Elementary School District 33 to continue providing weekly deliveries to families impacted by COVID-19.

We cannot thank the volunteers enough. Lida, Jon, Ann, Dave, and Lynne - you have made a difference in the community! A special shout out to our Steering Committee member, Kyle Reschke, for bringing these volunteers together.

#togetherisbetter

Looking for a new book to read? Take time to walk to any of the neighborhood Little Free Libraries found around the community. There are also Sidewalk Libraries found at Indian Knoll Elementary School and Wego Preschool on Forest Ave.

Here are locations for 4 Little Free Libraries:
325 Spencer ( in front of West Chicago Police Department)
648 Ingalton Ave. (Two houses south of Turner Elementary School )

820 E. Grand Lake Blvd. (Not Pictured)
216 Sherman Ave (close to Trinity Preschool) Not Pictured

More locations to come soon! #ILSchoolsStepUp #theD33effect

post_text: Some more great ways to continue having fun and learning at the same time. #ILSchoolsStepUp #theD33effect
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Experimento #1

Wego Preschool
March 25 at 7:10 AM ¬∑

Hello friends! Today is Spirit-Wear-Wednesday! Miss Desiree is wearing one of her favorite penguin shirts. Check out the cool science experiment you can try at home! Don't forget to post your pics here or on SeeSaw.

How you do it:
Use a funnel to add 1/3 cup baking soda to the inside of a balloon.
Fill a plastic bottle with approximately 1 cup vinegar.
Attach the balloon to the mouth of the plastic bottle, then lift the balloon upright so the baking soda falls and causes the reaction.

https://youtu.be/CtK5hc8dmjk

Thank you People's Resource Center for your continued support of West Chicago families. A huge shout out to Erika (market Coordinator) and her team of volunteers for going above and beyond to support the community! #togetherisbetter

shared_text:
Currier Elementary School Specials
March 24 at 9:24 AM ¬∑

Good Morning!

Today I'd like to pose a challenge to all of my Currier students called the COLOR WHEEL CHALLENGE.

Your mission is to make a color wheel, at home, without any art supplies. Make sure you set up your wheel in the correct order (Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Blue, Purple). This is a great way to practice keen observation and a fun way to use your creative brain. What objects can you find around your house to create this array of colors??

When you are done with your color wheel, take a picture of it and you can share it with me through ClassDojo messages, on your art Seesaw portfolio, or send it as a private message to the Currier Specials Facebook page.

Don't forget to put everything back where you found it once you are done :)

Have fun!

Currier Elementary School

post_text:
FEBRUARY SUB OF THE MONTH IS: ELLEN VICIAN

Ellen found out about our district after attending a substitute training at the Regional Office of Education. She came to our district to try her hand at subbing and as the testimony to her states, over two year later she is still in our preschool. She works primarily in Scott Lutz‚Äôs classroom and he has shared his thoughts on Ellen.

"Ellen has been such an integral member of my classroom. She is amazing with the children, asks great questions to excel in her role, and she brings a measured calm with her every day. I'm sure she never imagined that she would still be subbing in my class 2 1/2 years later, but we are all better for it. Thank you Ellen for all that you do for the kids and the preschool!" #theD33effect

Together for Excellence! #D33Pride #D33Orgullo

Currier Elementary School Specials
March 18 at 11:31 AM ¬∑

Hello Currier Families!
Go Noodle has some active screen time options for families, at family.gonoodle.com . Brainercise is a fun choice for all ages, and one that challenges me! If you are looking to burn some energy, check out Maximo. You will find the Electric Slide, the Hokey Pokey, the Chicken Dance, and a lot of other fun choices. When it is time to calm down, try Flow. Have fun and take good care of yourselves!
I miss you!
Mrs. Kearney

The Raccoon and the Bee Tree, A Native American Tale

Spider Stories, A Jamaican Folk Tale

The Love of Talwalpin and Kowinka, An Australian Aboriginal Story

The People Who Hugged Trees, A Classic Folk Tale from Rajasthan, India

Why Bats Fly at Night, A Legend of the Kona People of Sierra Leone, Africa

Turnip Soup, A Russian Folk Tale

post_text:
Do you remember Future Problem Solvers?

It's back in District 33 and over 60 students in the Gifted and Talented Programs at Currier Elementary School, Gary Elementary School, Wegner Elementary School and Leman Middle School participated in the Future Problem Solvers Regional Competition on Feb. 1, 2020.

Future Problem Solvers International uses a research-based problem solving process to develop critical and creative thinking skills, increase awareness of the future, and enhance communication and collaboration. Students worked in small teams of 3-4 to apply this problem solving process to a fictitious problem of the future.

Stay tuned for results!

Together for Excellence! #D33Pride #D33Orgullo
text:
Do you remember Future Problem Solvers?

It's back in District 33 and over 60 students in the Gifted and Talented Programs at Currier Elementary School, Gary Elementary School, Wegner Elementary School and Leman Middle School participated in the Future Problem Solvers Regional Competition on Feb. 1, 2020.

Future Problem Solvers International uses a research-based problem solving process to develop critical and creative thinking skills, increase awareness of the future, and enhance communication and collaboration. Students worked in small teams of 3-4 to apply this problem solving process to a fictitious problem of the future.

Stay tuned for results!

Together for Excellence! #D33Pride #D33Orgullo

The joke was in a Thyra Heder Books called Alfie: (The Turtle that Disappeared) but there was no punchline. So, Ms. Anderson walked her students through the process of creating a punchline and submitted them to the author.
